This is my second time participating in the Desmos Math Art Contest. I participated the first year and got finalist with my graph on special relativity, I skipped the second year, and here I am for year three.

  Here before you is fully-playable chess recreated in Desmos. Chess is by far my favorite board game. This is my third time recreating it in an engine that was never designed with chess in mind. It has all of the movement rules coded in including castling and en passant, as well as check and checkmate detection.

  You can move the camera's perspective by grabbing the background and moving it around to get a different view. To move a piece, click the square that it is on and the legal moves will be displayed for you.

  In case you're on a slower system, you can adjust the Animation Speed and Camera Speed to make them more fit for the lower framerate, or disable the fancy features.

  To reset the game, click Reset up in the corner.

  Everything you need to play is on the graph to the right, so feel free to collapse the expression list.

  If you're interested in seeing the type of stuff that I do, here's my YouTube channel: https://www.youtube.com/c/Dominexis"},{"type":"text","id":"1288","text":"  For helping me with this graph, I would like to thank the Lord for granting me the time, inspiration, and the ability to finish this project in time.
